The paper focuses on using deep reinforcement learning to optimize stock trading strategy, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the evaluation of the proposed approach, which involves comparing it with traditional portfolio allocation strategies, such as the min-variance portfolio allocation strategy, which falls under the category of computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.CE). Additionally, the paper involves the use of an agent to make decisions in a dynamic environment, which falls under the category of multi-agent systems (cs.MA) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
